WEBVTT

00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:17.100
Nic: Hi, I'm Nic Steenhout, and this is The Work Between. This

00:00:17.100 --> 00:00:20.940
Nic: podcast is recorded on the traditional, ancestral, and

00:00:21.030 --> 00:00:25.785
Nic: unceded territory of the Stó:lō Coast Salish people, the people

00:00:25.785 --> 00:00:29.265
Nic: of the river, whose presence in the Fraser Valley stretches back

00:00:29.265 --> 00:00:33.765
Nic: of years I named this territory because it belongs

00:00:33.765 --> 00:00:37.845
Nic: with what this show is about the ways we decide whose lives

00:00:37.845 --> 00:00:42.585
Nic: are valued whose work is taken seriously and whose experiences

00:00:42.585 --> 00:00:47.370
Nic: are treated as problems to be managed those decisions shape

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:54.450
Nic: everything this show sits inside that this is was and

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:58.590
Nic: always will be First Nations land that's not a formality

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:07.290
Nic: It's consistent with everything I and this show stand for. My

00:01:07.290 --> 00:01:13.875
Nic: guest today is Dr. Alessandra Springman. I know her as Sondi.

00:01:13.875 --> 00:01:18.315
Nic: Sondi is a planetary scientist with a PhD from the Lunar and

00:01:18.315 --> 00:01:23.595
Nic: Planetary Laboratory at the University of Arizona. She spent

00:01:23.595 --> 00:01:27.435
Nic: years studying asteroids and comets, and her work has

00:01:27.435 --> 00:01:31.905
Nic: included the NASA OSIRIS-REx asteroid sample, returning

00:01:31.905 --> 00:01:36.480
Nic: mission, and two years of planetary radar observation at

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:43.500
Nic: Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico. She quilts. Her quilting

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:50.280
Nic: practice lives on Instagram at at intergalactic cactus. So

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:54.090
Nic: today we're talking about quilts, what draws her to the

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:57.525
Nic: work, and what making things by hand means when your

00:01:57.525 --> 00:02:01.485
Nic: professional life is built around looking towards outer

00:02:01.485 --> 00:02:04.575
Nic: space. Sondy, welcome to The Work Between.

00:02:05.265 --> 00:02:06.165
Sondy: Thank you,

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:13.350
Nic: Now, for my listeners, I have to be open. Um Sondy and I go

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:17.610
Nic: way back and we've been talking about quilting a lot but let's

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:22.970
Nic: let's try and formalize things a little bit tell me a little bit

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.200
Nic: about your creative practice what is it that you do

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:29.900
Nic: obviously quilting but tell me more about that

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:35.270
Sondy: for the most part when I make quilts I am turning

00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:41.080
Sondy: secondhand fabric into something more interesting than stuff that

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:43.780
Sondy: doesn't get sold at the thrift store that may wind up in a

00:02:43.810 --> 00:02:49.300
Sondy: landfill. The project that I'm working on now is a lot of work

00:02:49.390 --> 00:02:51.940
Sondy: shirts and work pants from an uncle figure of mine who's a

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.250
Sondy: contractor who builds boats, repairs boats. He met his wife

00:02:57.370 --> 00:03:00.870
Sondy: while they were working at a boat yard. She was the manager

00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:04.980
Sondy: and he rose up in the ranks because he could weld and he

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:10.380
Sondy: was smart um he's a he's a real uh he's so we were going through his

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:13.500
Sondy: clothes a couple years ago when I was staying um in a little

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:16.410
Sondy: cottage on their property and he was saying that he would love

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:18.960
Sondy: a quilt made from secondhand shirts because it was it would

00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:25.580
Sondy: be soft I said okay richard um so here we are almost two

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:30.620
Sondy: years later and it's been a really fun way to figure out

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:33.950
Sondy: how do you take something you know how do you take a set of

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:36.740
Sondy: half a dozen work shirts and carhartt pants all made of

00:03:36.830 --> 00:03:41.950
Sondy: canvas and denim and other tough materials and make them make

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:45.490
Sondy: them something soft and how do you arrange them in an

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:49.660
Sondy: pleasing way and how do you do it in a way that

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:51.820
Sondy: doesn't make you want to lose your mind, or if you are going

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:55.690
Sondy: to lose your mind, providing for losing your mind

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:59.560
Sondy: in the process. So I'm doing something called quilt as you

00:03:59.650 --> 00:04:04.470
Sondy: go, which involves cutting out the batting for each little part

00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:08.430
Sondy: of the quilt before hand, rather than sewing the top of the

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.030
Sondy: quilt, sewing the back of the quilt, and then sewing the top

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:14.100
Sondy: of the quilt, the batting and the back of the quilt together

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:19.920
Sondy: in uh one big sandwich and so for this I'm making tiny little

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:25.010
Sondy: hexagon sandwiches and rather than lose my mind cutting out

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:30.290
Sondy: each hexagon of batting and fabric uh by myself by hand I went

00:04:30.290 --> 00:04:33.350
Sondy: to the library makerspace and used the laser cutter to laser

00:04:33.470 --> 00:04:38.630
Sondy: cut the batting into hexagons and to laser cut his uh denim work

00:04:38.690 --> 00:04:42.100
Sondy: pants and work shirts into in canvas work pants and work

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:45.580
Sondy: shirts into hexagons so I didn't ruin all my uh cutting tools

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:49.750
Sondy: at home so it's been a fun way to you know take something as

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:53.260
Sondy: mundane as you know the clothes off his back but you

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:55.540
Sondy: know clothes that have been well loved and some of them have fun

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:58.120
Sondy: paint stains and some of them you know there's the fading

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:02.910
Sondy: that's really interesting under the seams uh men's work shirts

00:05:03.210 --> 00:05:07.080
Sondy: often have like a little I think it's a pleat at the back

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:11.760
Sondy: of the neck and so the that area under that doesn't fade as

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:14.910
Sondy: much as the rest of the shirt. So I've managed to capture that

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:18.690
Sondy: in a few places. So I think it's a really fun way to take

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:21.890
Sondy: something, you know, like his, you know, these clothes that

00:05:21.890 --> 00:05:24.380
Sondy: are such a fundamental part of us, you know, they're close to

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:26.630
Sondy: our heart, we wear them out, and they sort of fade into the

00:05:26.690 --> 00:05:29.120
Sondy: woodwork, and to turn them into something soft, something

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:32.570
Sondy: comforting, and something that will, you know, keep him warm.

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:37.700
Nic: how do you take something that's not inherently soft like

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:43.390
Nic: denim or or work canvas and make it into something soft and cozy

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.210
Sondy: first of all you give those garments to someone who

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:48.460
Sondy: will wear them until they are worn out and they have been

00:05:48.730 --> 00:05:51.850
Sondy: washed so many times that they are incredibly soft on their

00:05:52.030 --> 00:05:55.210
Sondy: own and then one of the things I have figured out in quilting

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:58.900
Sondy: is if your fabric is ugly or if your fabric is otherwise too

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:02.940
Sondy: much if you cut it small enough it suddenly is less ugly

00:06:03.270 --> 00:06:09.600
Sondy: or less firm so having these um pieces of you know canvas

00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:13.110
Sondy: carhartt work pants cut to hexagons that are about six

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.860
Sondy: inches tall makes it much easier to have them be soft and the

00:06:16.860 --> 00:06:23.630
Sondy: whole quilt isn't denim or canvas there's a lot of um there's

00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:26.840
Sondy: thrift store shirts there's shirts from friends there's

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:30.620
Sondy: some corduroy pants in here there's quilting cotton all the

00:06:30.860 --> 00:06:34.970
Sondy: backs the hexagons are quilting cottons so there's a

00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:38.210
Sondy: huge variety so if you don't have the hard things dominating

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:40.420
Sondy: your quilt you can get away with a lot

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:43.270
Nic: how did you learn quilting

00:06:44.769 --> 00:06:49.059
Sondy: well in 2020 uh in march 2020 when my roommate at the

00:06:49.119 --> 00:06:51.219
Sondy: time and I were like well we're at home what do we do

00:06:51.249 --> 00:06:55.809
Sondy: with ourselves she had gone to fashion design school. And so

00:06:55.959 --> 00:06:58.959
Sondy: she had been an accomplished sewist. She had done costume

00:06:58.989 --> 00:07:03.569
Sondy: design in New York, including Broadway musicals. And so she

00:07:03.719 --> 00:07:07.289
Sondy: was, she was very competent. And so we said, let's sew some

00:07:07.589 --> 00:07:10.769
Sondy: masks. And I thought I knew how to sew. I'd, you know, done some

00:07:10.829 --> 00:07:13.709
Sondy: basic garment sewing. I'd sewed my prom dress in high school.

00:07:14.849 --> 00:07:17.939
Sondy: And, you know, after I borrowed a sewing machine from a friend

00:07:17.999 --> 00:07:22.339
Sondy: and Carrie looks at my sewing and she, you know, you can tell

00:07:22.549 --> 00:07:24.919
Sondy: the thoughts are going through her head. Like, wow, Sondy, you

00:07:25.039 --> 00:07:27.949
Sondy: think you could sew? That's a really nice idea you

00:07:28.009 --> 00:07:32.719
Sondy: have there. But she taught me kind of how to sew as an adult

00:07:32.809 --> 00:07:35.899
Sondy: rather than seat of the pants sewing that my mother had taught

00:07:35.959 --> 00:07:41.589
Sondy: me. And once you do something hundreds of times, and we sewed

00:07:41.979 --> 00:07:46.329
Sondy: 500 masks. I had a spreadsheet tracking all this. Once you do

00:07:46.419 --> 00:07:51.309
Sondy: something hundreds of times, you get decent at it. So I sort of

00:07:51.519 --> 00:07:54.519
Sondy: got more consistent with my pinning, got more consistent

00:07:54.639 --> 00:07:59.739
Sondy: with stitching, learned some binding, learned all sorts of

00:07:59.919 --> 00:08:03.419
Sondy: things, learned some very silly couture techniques, which I've

00:08:03.479 --> 00:08:05.549
Sondy: never really used since, but it's good to know that they

00:08:05.579 --> 00:08:11.579
Sondy: exist. And, you know, after it became clear that supply chains

00:08:11.699 --> 00:08:18.509
Sondy: had resolved themselves and we could get good N95 masks. Again, I

00:08:18.629 --> 00:08:22.639
Sondy: had all the scrap fabric left. And one of my friends in town

00:08:22.699 --> 00:08:26.779
Sondy: was an astronomer who was moving to a job at an observatory in

00:08:26.779 --> 00:08:29.179
Sondy: Hawaii, and she was downsizing. And she gave me a bunch of

00:08:29.209 --> 00:08:32.839
Sondy: fabric that I didn't realize was like fancy designer quilting

00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:36.199
Sondy: fabric until I had all these scraps sitting around and said,

00:08:36.289 --> 00:08:39.829
Sondy: what should I do with them? Uh, and I'm, I'm Jewish, but you know,

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:42.969
Sondy: most of my friends are celebrate Christmas. And I decided to make

00:08:43.059 --> 00:08:46.689
Sondy: a Christmas stocking for a friend out of these scraps and

00:08:47.709 --> 00:08:50.139
Sondy: didn't quite realize that what I was doing was quilting until I

00:08:50.139 --> 00:08:54.369
Sondy: had done it and realized, Oh, this is, this is quilting. I

00:08:54.489 --> 00:08:56.709
Sondy: should, I should learn more about this. So I went to the

00:08:56.769 --> 00:08:59.889
Sondy: library and I went to the shelf of the library that had quilting

00:08:59.979 --> 00:09:04.979
Sondy: books. And I this was you know a neighborhood branch it

00:09:04.979 --> 00:09:07.919
Sondy: wasn't the main branch and I grabbed the five most

00:09:07.979 --> 00:09:11.009
Sondy: interesting books out of six that they had on the shelf and

00:09:11.009 --> 00:09:13.769
Sondy: I took them home and I found one by Blair Stocker called

00:09:13.859 --> 00:09:18.209
Sondy: Wisecraft Quilts and she turns fabrics into meaningful

00:09:18.419 --> 00:09:22.039
Sondy: patchwork and I read this book you know I opened this book I

00:09:22.189 --> 00:09:25.579
Sondy: read her philosophy and I turned a few pages in and I saw

00:09:25.729 --> 00:09:29.119
Sondy: this quilt where she was using the value or the brightness of

00:09:29.149 --> 00:09:32.899
Sondy: fabrics rather than the color or the pattern to dictate the

00:09:33.079 --> 00:09:37.519
Sondy: pattern dictate the layout of the quilt and I was completely

00:09:37.639 --> 00:09:43.599
Sondy: sold and probably within within three weeks of making that

00:09:43.689 --> 00:09:46.959
Sondy: Christmas stocking I had put an alert on Craigslist for sewing

00:09:47.049 --> 00:09:50.349
Sondy: machines at estate sales and yard sales I had driven 45

00:09:50.589 --> 00:09:54.549
Sondy: minutes down to a suburb of Tucson. I threw elbows. I got a

00:09:54.729 --> 00:10:01.019
Sondy: gigantic Janome sewing machine that Ginger Downing had

00:10:01.199 --> 00:10:05.729
Sondy: spent like $2,600 on new that I got for $600. And it came with all

00:10:05.759 --> 00:10:09.359
Sondy: the accessories. And I have sewn so much on that machine since.

00:10:10.019 --> 00:10:12.449
Sondy: And I've made some pretty cool quilts, if I don't say so

00:10:12.719 --> 00:10:16.049
Sondy: myself. It's been really fun to finally feel like

00:10:16.109 --> 00:10:20.099
Sondy: I have a creative practice. Both of my parents are artists my

00:10:20.189 --> 00:10:25.939
Sondy: mom has done oil painting and acrylic uh big big canvases she's

00:10:26.179 --> 00:10:28.669
Sondy: done some mixed media but she really sticks to like big

00:10:29.719 --> 00:10:33.739
Sondy: abstract acrylic canvas works my dad was a portrait

00:10:33.739 --> 00:10:37.069
Sondy: photographer for most of his career he photographed Georgia

00:10:37.189 --> 00:10:43.179
Sondy: O'Keeffe in 1974 at Ghost Ranch so he's you know so my

00:10:43.749 --> 00:10:46.569
Sondy: mother's father was an animator her mother was an illustrator

00:10:49.359 --> 00:10:53.859
Sondy: my dad's mother sewed and she crocheted and she knitted so

00:10:54.639 --> 00:10:56.529
Sondy: you know I come from this family of creatives and I'd

00:10:56.529 --> 00:10:59.079
Sondy: never really done anything regularly and I think everyone

00:10:59.109 --> 00:11:02.459
Sondy: was sort of like sitting around waiting for me to do something

00:11:02.519 --> 00:11:06.389
Sondy: consistently so when I finally started quilting I think

00:11:06.419 --> 00:11:09.629
Sondy: everyone I think my mom in particular breathed a sigh of

00:11:09.659 --> 00:11:13.289
Sondy: relief and four months after I started quilting she came to

00:11:13.289 --> 00:11:16.229
Sondy: visit me in Tucson and I was picking up my sewing machine

00:11:16.289 --> 00:11:20.809
Sondy: from being serviced at the, um, the sewing machine store and she

00:11:20.959 --> 00:11:24.289
Sondy: paid for it. And she's like, no, I want to encourage this. So it's

00:11:24.349 --> 00:11:28.189
Sondy: been, it's been cool to get into quilting. It's been cool to find

00:11:28.279 --> 00:11:30.349
Sondy: out how many people around me quilt or know someone who

00:11:30.439 --> 00:11:35.359
Sondy: quilts, uh, you know, someone's mom tried quilting and she gave me

00:11:37.069 --> 00:11:42.429
Sondy: the, what they call a pig, a project in a grocery bag of her

00:11:42.579 --> 00:11:45.039
Sondy: first attempt at quilting and she decided she didn't like

00:11:45.099 --> 00:11:47.409
Sondy: quilting after she'd started that. And I looked at what she'd

00:11:47.799 --> 00:11:49.599
Sondy: done and I said, yeah, of course you didn't like

00:11:49.719 --> 00:11:53.589
Sondy: quilting, Pat. You were not, no one taught you how to do this

00:11:53.799 --> 00:11:56.109
Sondy: properly. No one taught you how to cut your fabric properly. Of

00:11:56.169 --> 00:12:01.919
Sondy: course you hated this. So, you know, it's fun. And then I've

00:12:02.039 --> 00:12:07.079
Sondy: moved up to Boulder a few years ago and through a desperate

00:12:07.199 --> 00:12:11.159
Sondy: post on the Young and Millennial Quilters Facebook group, found a

00:12:11.279 --> 00:12:13.559
Sondy: wonderful long arm quilter up here and joined the Boulder

00:12:13.619 --> 00:12:17.249
Sondy: Modern Quilt Guild. And it's been great to meet other people

00:12:17.429 --> 00:12:20.399
Sondy: who are really interested in secondhand materials quilting.

00:12:21.419 --> 00:12:25.519
Sondy: There's one guy in the Quilt Guild, Elu Hernandez, who's a bit

00:12:25.549 --> 00:12:29.269
Sondy: of a big deal making quilt set of reclaimed jeans. And so he's

00:12:29.299 --> 00:12:33.169
Sondy: been really encouraging about this project. And there was a

00:12:33.829 --> 00:12:36.439
Sondy: Quilt Guild open sew and he said, give me seven of those

00:12:36.499 --> 00:12:38.509
Sondy: hexagons. I want to take them home to sew them together for

00:12:38.569 --> 00:12:46.479
Sondy: you. So he took seven of the 188 hexagon pieces and sewed them

00:12:46.539 --> 00:12:50.379
Sondy: together. So now I get to add his name to this quilt. So it's

00:12:50.439 --> 00:12:53.829
Sondy: been really fun to learn this, to find the community,

00:12:53.949 --> 00:12:58.479
Sondy: community. I try to read a lot, you know, random quilt

00:12:58.899 --> 00:13:02.969
Sondy: books, blogs. The Facebook group has been fabulous and

00:13:02.999 --> 00:13:05.069
Sondy: educational. There's a lot of Facebook groups that are badly

00:13:05.159 --> 00:13:10.019
Sondy: moderated or that tolerate very bad politics and behavior from

00:13:10.109 --> 00:13:12.809
Sondy: their members. And this Facebook group is, I would say, it's one

00:13:12.809 --> 00:13:18.989
Sondy: of the things that keeps me vaguely active on

00:13:19.079 --> 00:13:23.719
Sondy: Facebook. And by vaguely active, I mean logging in twice a month to ask

00:13:23.749 --> 00:13:28.669
Sondy: a question or see posts there. So I've enjoyed the community.

00:13:29.389 --> 00:13:31.039
Sondy: I've enjoyed being able to make things.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:33.920
Nic: I want to come back to community in a little bit, But

00:13:34.850 --> 00:13:39.470
Nic: before we explore that, I want to talk influences. Obviously,

00:13:39.950 --> 00:13:46.690
Nic: your family background is very much into creativity, but it

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:51.340
Nic: sounds like nobody really quilts. Have they?

00:13:54.130 --> 00:13:58.510
Sondy: My dad has started quilting in the last few years.

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:03.840
Nic: As a follow up on what you're doing, right? So the

00:14:05.100 --> 00:14:09.180
Nic: influence into quilting from their creative and artistic

00:14:09.270 --> 00:14:14.400
Nic: endeavors, has that tickled through or is just, tell me

00:14:14.490 --> 00:14:15.450
Nic: about that relationship.

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:18.780
Sondy: I think it's interesting because my mother

00:14:19.050 --> 00:14:22.880
Sondy: loves color. She loves reds and oranges and

00:14:22.940 --> 00:14:26.510
Sondy: yellows and she loves her blues and her greens and things of

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:30.440
Sondy: that nature. But my mother doesn't really think about value

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:35.480
Sondy: in her her paintings she doesn't think about the contrast

00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:38.540
Sondy: between colors she just says you know she's a very intuitive

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:45.490
Sondy: painter and you know she went to she I think she went to art

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:50.500
Sondy: school for a little bit she had some um post-college art education

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:52.420
Sondy: so I know you know I know she's familiar with color

00:14:52.540 --> 00:14:55.450
Sondy: theory I know she's familiar with value and contrast and

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:59.860
Sondy: tints and tones and shades and all that um but she you know I

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:03.210
Sondy: she knows all that but it's all you know in her heart at this

00:15:03.330 --> 00:15:07.080
Sondy: point we've talked about sort of like patterns and scale but

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:10.290
Sondy: you know she she creates with paint she creates very

00:15:10.590 --> 00:15:14.820
Sondy: fundamental she creates in a very fundamental way with paint

00:15:14.970 --> 00:15:17.070
Sondy: whereas you know I'm using things that already exist and

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:19.890
Sondy: I'll look around you know at the fabric and say hmm this

00:15:19.950 --> 00:15:22.880
Sondy: would be good for this I think it's a very different creative

00:15:22.970 --> 00:15:27.590
Sondy: process than than what my mom does and I have some of the

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:31.670
Sondy: fabrics that her mother designed as an illustrator for the launch of

00:15:31.730 --> 00:15:34.700
