Sondy: in the ecosystem folks say they uh they need to they need to

00:17:30.739 --> 00:17:33.469
Sondy: be used so for folks who are not familiar with singer

00:17:33.559 --> 00:17:37.309
Sondy: featherweights Singer made these lovely little

00:17:37.399 --> 00:17:41.709
Sondy: sewing machines between the 1930s and the 1960s. And they are

00:17:42.249 --> 00:17:45.819
Sondy: mechanical. They draw 0.7 amps, less if you put an

00:17:45.879 --> 00:17:48.699
Sondy: LED bulb in them. I mean, they draw less current than your

00:17:48.789 --> 00:17:52.899
Sondy: phone does when it charges. And they are, some of them have been

00:17:52.959 --> 00:17:56.229
Sondy: running for 90 years. If you keep servicing them and keep

00:17:56.289 --> 00:17:58.629
Sondy: putting oil and grease on them, they will run for another 90

00:17:58.689 --> 00:18:01.319
Sondy: years. I mean, they are the most robust little

00:18:01.349 --> 00:18:03.899
Sondy: machines. And I like to say that they are the most heterosexual

00:18:03.959 --> 00:18:06.569
Sondy: sewing machines of all time, because you will not find a

00:18:06.629 --> 00:18:11.459
Sondy: straighter stitch on any other sewing machine. So it's been

00:18:11.579 --> 00:18:14.609
Sondy: fun to learn the basics of featherweight maintenance

00:18:15.299 --> 00:18:18.569
Sondy: and where to grease and where to oil and how to

00:18:18.659 --> 00:18:23.989
Sondy: clean things with kerosene and how to adjust the timing and

00:18:24.379 --> 00:18:29.929
Sondy: what has changed in the intervening uh 81 years since my

00:18:30.019 --> 00:18:34.639
Sondy: sewing machine has been made and what has not in you know

00:18:34.729 --> 00:18:36.919
Sondy: what remains the same between this machine and modern

00:18:36.949 --> 00:18:39.499
Sondy: machines like the needle that this machine uses it's the same

00:18:39.529 --> 00:18:41.109
Sondy: needle that modern machines do

00:18:42.009 --> 00:18:42.069
Nic: yeah

00:18:42.370 --> 00:18:46.090
